                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3hx1670z/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>so very kind of her to gratify me by such an attention.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">What a delightful discovery is that of\n                    <persName>Daguerres</persName><lb/> lot certainly should be much better than\n                the<lb/> ancients for see the advantages we possess\n                <persName>Daguerres</persName><lb/> that give us the positive though inanimate\n                presence<lb/> of those we love. Rail roads that swift as Eagles<lb/> wings bring\n                them to us &amp; most extraordinarily the Telegra<lb/>phic wires, which with a\n                velocity incredible bring us in<lb/>formation (of those separated from us) of sorrow\n                or hap-<lb/>piness! Yet man is no better his passions still<lb/> unchecked his\n                propensities still leading him to evil<lb/> temptation lives with her smiles in\n                spite of all the<lb/> advantages which this age of improvement &amp; discovery<lb/>\n                affords us. <persName>Mrs. Henry</persName> is better, Rumor with her poisoned<lb/>\n                tongue has said that a change had come over here relig<lb/>ious feelings &amp; that\n                she did not find that consolation in her<lb/> own faith that she required. This I\n                could not bring my<lb/> heart to believe &amp; contradicted the report although\n                it<lb/> came from authority hard to doubt. I could believe<lb/> that with the body\n                in torture &amp; the mind enfeebled<lb/> that she might be vacillating (because my\n                friend wants<lb/> division of character) &amp; beg the prayers of any good<lb/> man\n                But as I had acted with her had seen how com<lb/>pletely she was satisfied with her\n                own faith, I rejected<lb/> the idea and believed that as she regained her\n                health<lb/> she would regain confidence in her own faith!<lb/>\n                <persName>C'ol. Myers</persName> has written to beg that all reports<lb/> injurious\n                to him should be refuted for there was<lb/> no truth in it. <persName>Mrs.\n                    Bryan</persName> is with her &amp; it<lb/> is said that <persName>Mrs.\n                    Henry</persName> will never allow</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3hx1670z/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
            }
